                                            <content type="html">
                            &lt;p&gt;Wow! What a wonderful repo for refactoring practice; multiple language and multiple challenges. I&#039;m working through yahtzee now and hope to point attendees at Code Craftsman Saturdays (&lt;a href=&quot;http://goo.gl/sLTR9&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;http://goo.gl/sLTR9&lt;/a&gt;) at this repo next month. Thank you so much for putting this out there. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Will happily provide feedback after the session on the 14th.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bob Allen&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;br/&gt; &lt;cite&gt;Emily Bache said:&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote cite=&quot;http://coderetreat.org/forum/topics/last-session-doing-gilded-rose-kata?groupUrl=facilitators&amp;amp;commentId=6456126%3AComment%3A16482&amp;amp;groupId=6456126%3AGroup%3A901#6456126Comment17627&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;xg_user_generated&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;I&#039;ve used the gilded rose kata with various groups, and I think it is a good one. Before you can start refactoring, you have to write a bunch of tests, and you can practice designing really good ones. If you do it properly, you won&#039;t have time in 45 minutes to get to the refactoring part.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I have another refactoring kata that I think I&#039;m going to suggest as an alternative for the participants in my code retreat. (About 1/3 of the people there will have already been to at least one of my previous code retreats, so I think they in particular might appreciate doing something different.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I plan to show them &quot;Tennis&quot; which I&#039;ve got on my github page along with Gilded Rose&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a rel=&quot;nofollow&quot; href=&quot;https://github.com/emilybache/Refactoring-Katas/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;https://github.com/emilybache/Refactoring-Katas/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The difference compared with Gilded Rose is that there is a full suite of tests provided, so you can just get on with the refactoring. There are also three versions of the code to be refactored, so you can practice different kinds of refactorings.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;                        </content>
                    
