                    <title>Hello Anthony,
This might be…</title>
                    <link rel="alternate" href="http://coderetreat.org/xn/detail/6456126:Comment:16482"/>
                                        <id>tag:coderetreat.org,2012-11-20:6456126:Comment:16482</id>
                                        <updated>2012-11-20T02:41:59.789Z</updated>
                    
                                            <author>
                            <name>Jim Hurne</name>
                            <uri>http://coderetreat.org/profile/JimHurne</uri>
                        </author>
                    
                    <summary type="html">
                        &lt;p&gt;Hello Anthony,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This might be a good thing to try if you have a group who have attended several coderetreats in the past.  I think I like the suggestion of using the Gilded Rose kata rather than asking people to first write really terrible code. We only have so much time at a Coderetreat and it seems a little wasteful to ask participants to practice writing bad code.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, if you start with something like the Gilded Rose kata, then participants can jump right into trying to…&lt;/p&gt;                    </summary>

                                            <content type="html">
                            &lt;p&gt;Hello Anthony,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This might be a good thing to try if you have a group who have attended several coderetreats in the past.  I think I like the suggestion of using the Gilded Rose kata rather than asking people to first write really terrible code. We only have so much time at a Coderetreat and it seems a little wasteful to ask participants to practice writing bad code.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, if you start with something like the Gilded Rose kata, then participants can jump right into trying to improve the code. The downside to using Gilded Rose is that you&#039;ll be stepping away from GoL and participants will have to learn a new problem for the last session of the day.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I don&#039;t think I would attempt ether varaints with a group relatively new to coderetreat. We already cover a lot of topics and concepts throughout the day. Trying to mix in a little bit of legacy coderetreat might just end up overwhelming or confusing participants. I think it would be better to keep the day primarily focused on the fundamentals and to save the legacy code exercises for a Legacy Coderetreat.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Of course, you can always use the coderetreat as a place to advertize an upcoming Legacy Coderetreat...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Jim++&lt;/p&gt;                        </content>
                    
